1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,220
This is my father, Mervin Tilbury.

2
00:00:02,220 --> 00:00:04,770
He's one of the hardest
working people I know,

3
00:00:04,770 --> 00:00:05,610
and as a kid,

4
00:00:05,610 --> 00:00:08,970
I remember him working in a
factory job making cable ties

5
00:00:08,970 --> 00:00:11,130
and a side hustle cutting grass,

6
00:00:11,130 --> 00:00:14,820
so he could provide for me and
my mom and my three sisters.

7
00:00:14,820 --> 00:00:18,180
He'd stash away any extra money
he made in a shoebox as well

8
00:00:18,180 --> 00:00:20,730
as a bank account that
paid little to no interest,

9
00:00:20,730 --> 00:00:23,070
hoping that one day he could quit his job

10
00:00:23,070 --> 00:00:24,390
working in the factory.

11
00:00:24,390 --> 00:00:25,830
When my uncle invested some

12
00:00:25,830 --> 00:00:27,660
of his money in the stock market,

13
00:00:27,660 --> 00:00:30,570
my dad said it was an
extremely risky move.

14
00:00:30,570 --> 00:00:33,300
Unfortunately, what my dad didn't realize

15
00:00:33,300 --> 00:00:35,790
is that he was also playing a risky game.

16
00:00:35,790 --> 00:00:37,740
Can you see where this story's going?

17
00:00:37,740 --> 00:00:39,330
Every year, my father's money

18
00:00:39,330 --> 00:00:41,760
was losing value due to inflation.

19
00:00:41,760 --> 00:00:43,830
This is just what happens over time.

20
00:00:43,830 --> 00:00:45,180
As more money is printed,

21
00:00:45,180 --> 00:00:47,850
the money in circulation
becomes less valuable.

22
00:00:47,850 --> 00:00:51,300
This meant he was never able
to quit his job in the factory.

23
00:00:51,300 --> 00:00:53,310
The thought of my money being eaten

24
00:00:53,310 --> 00:00:55,830
away by inflation scared me so much

25
00:00:55,830 --> 00:00:58,260
that I've made sure to
invest throughout my life.

26
00:00:58,260 --> 00:01:01,410
As a result, not only
have I beaten inflation,

27
00:01:01,410 --> 00:01:03,300
but my investments actually now grow

28
00:01:03,300 --> 00:01:06,720
by around $17,000 a week on their own,

29
00:01:06,720 --> 00:01:09,450
which over my lifetime
has made me millions.

30
00:01:09,450 --> 00:01:11,100
I'm no financial advisor,

31
00:01:11,100 --> 00:01:13,410
but I am someone that's
been there and done it.

32
00:01:13,410 --> 00:01:15,210
That's why I'm making this video.

33
00:01:15,210 --> 00:01:18,180
It's exactly what I wish
I had when I was younger.

34
00:01:18,180 --> 00:01:21,180
How can I make money investing in stocks?

35
00:01:21,180 --> 00:01:22,485
To make money,

36
00:01:22,485 --> 00:01:23,970
we first need to beat the inflation issue.

37
00:01:23,970 --> 00:01:25,110
In the last 60 years,

38
00:01:25,110 --> 00:01:28,560
this average is out to
a rate of 3.8% per year.

39
00:01:28,560 --> 00:01:31,170
So if your money isn't growing
by more than this on its own,

40
00:01:31,170 --> 00:01:32,940
then you're getting poorer by the second.

41
00:01:32,940 --> 00:01:35,250
In a perfect world, you
would have a savings

42
00:01:35,250 --> 00:01:37,230
account that provides an average return

43
00:01:37,230 --> 00:01:39,300
of eight to 10% every year,

44
00:01:39,300 --> 00:01:42,690
so that you can both beat
inflation and earn some profit.

45
00:01:42,690 --> 00:01:45,540
Unfortunately, such savings
accounts don't exist.

46
00:01:45,540 --> 00:01:47,370
However, you can achieve returns

47
00:01:47,370 --> 00:01:49,680
like this by investing
in the stock market.

48
00:01:49,680 --> 00:01:53,040
A stock is a small part of a
company and when you buy it

49
00:01:53,040 --> 00:01:55,649
you become a shareholder, and
when you're a shareholder,

50
00:01:55,649 --> 00:01:57,870
there are two ways you can make money.

51
00:01:57,870 --> 00:01:59,070
Firstly, if the price

52
00:01:59,070 --> 00:02:01,620
of the stock goes up
during the time you own it,

53
00:02:01,620 --> 00:02:03,300
you can sell it for more than you paid.

54
00:02:03,300 --> 00:02:05,790
Secondly, you can receive dividends.

55
00:02:05,790 --> 00:02:08,340
Dividends are regular
payments to shareholders.

56
00:02:08,340 --> 00:02:11,280
Not all stocks pay
dividends, but if they do,

57
00:02:11,280 --> 00:02:12,870
this means that you can receive money

58
00:02:12,870 --> 00:02:14,670
without ever selling your stock.

59
00:02:14,670 --> 00:02:17,340
The magic really starts to
happen when you own a bunch

60
00:02:17,340 --> 00:02:20,430
of stocks that grow at an
average of 10% per year,

61
00:02:20,430 --> 00:02:23,550
because the interest applied
becomes larger and larger.

62
00:02:23,550 --> 00:02:26,670
This is called compound
interest, and I have to admit,

63
00:02:26,670 --> 00:02:28,680
a guilty pleasure of mine is messing

64
00:02:28,680 --> 00:02:31,830
around with online compound
interest calculators.

65
00:02:31,830 --> 00:02:33,150
Let's do one now.

66
00:02:33,150 --> 00:02:37,170
If you were able to invest $250 per month,

67
00:02:37,170 --> 00:02:39,630
at an 8% annual return,

68
00:02:39,630 --> 00:02:42,780
in 42 years, you'd be a millionaire

69
00:02:42,780 --> 00:02:45,840
and if you continue to do
this for another 10 years,

70
00:02:45,840 --> 00:02:49,050
you would actually have over
2 million in your account.

71
00:02:49,050 --> 00:02:51,510
Of course, if you wanted
to invest even more

72
00:02:51,510 --> 00:02:53,700
then that would just speed up the process.

73
00:02:53,700 --> 00:02:54,600
This is all based

74
00:02:54,600 --> 00:02:57,810
on historical average data
and it isn't guaranteed,

75
00:02:57,810 --> 00:03:00,090
but it's certainly been my experience.

76
00:03:00,090 --> 00:03:02,670
So as you can see, the
real secret ingredient

77
00:03:02,670 --> 00:03:04,980
to this millionaire formula is time,

78
00:03:04,980 --> 00:03:08,580
which brings me onto when
should I start investing.

79
00:03:08,580 --> 00:03:11,610
The short answer to this
is as soon as possible.

80
00:03:11,610 --> 00:03:13,860
The younger you start, the better.

81
00:03:13,860 --> 00:03:15,870
As you're giving your
investments more time

82
00:03:15,870 --> 00:03:17,220
to grow and compound.

83
00:03:17,220 --> 00:03:19,530
This also means you can take more risk,

84
00:03:19,530 --> 00:03:21,690
as your investments have time to recover

85
00:03:21,690 --> 00:03:24,240
if a stock market crash happens

86
00:03:24,240 --> 00:03:27,120
and it will happen, it always happens,

87
00:03:27,120 --> 00:03:30,150
but life isn't as easy as
this, as there are often things

88
00:03:30,150 --> 00:03:32,280
in the way preventing you from investing.

89
00:03:32,280 --> 00:03:34,500
So here's how I would structure things.

90
00:03:34,500 --> 00:03:36,145
First, you need to make sure you've paid

91
00:03:36,145 --> 00:03:39,660
off all high interest
debt like credit cards.

92
00:03:39,660 --> 00:03:40,860
Just think about it.

93
00:03:40,860 --> 00:03:43,860
There's no point trying to
make 10% in the stock market,

94
00:03:43,860 --> 00:03:47,400
if you are paying 15% to
a credit card company.

95
00:03:47,400 --> 00:03:50,670
Secondly, build up an emergency fund.

96
00:03:50,670 --> 00:03:53,460
This should be enough to
cover three to six months

97
00:03:53,460 --> 00:03:55,260
of your living expenses.

98
00:03:55,260 --> 00:03:57,630
This way, you are not
forced to sell your stocks

99
00:03:57,630 --> 00:03:59,280
in the event of an emergency

100
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:01,440
which can really ruin your progress.

101
00:04:01,440 --> 00:04:03,330
Once you've done both of these things,

102
00:04:03,330 --> 00:04:05,580
you are ready to start investing.

103
00:04:05,580 --> 00:04:07,170
If you are younger than 18,

104
00:04:07,170 --> 00:04:10,020
then it would be a great
idea to ask a parent to open

105
00:04:10,020 --> 00:04:14,190
up a custodial account, which
allows them to invest for you.

106
00:04:14,190 --> 00:04:16,890
This will give you such an
advantage in the future.

107
00:04:16,890 --> 00:04:18,900
Your next question is probably something

108
00:04:18,900 --> 00:04:21,840
along the lines of how
much should I invest?

109
00:04:21,840 --> 00:04:23,250
When you ask an investor,

110
00:04:23,250 --> 00:04:25,680
they'll probably say as much as possible.

111
00:04:25,680 --> 00:04:27,840
However, I have a different opinion.

112
00:04:27,840 --> 00:04:29,310
I made most of my money

113
00:04:29,310 --> 00:04:31,350
through starting different businesses

114
00:04:31,350 --> 00:04:35,130
and only use the stock market
to grow my wealth over time.

115
00:04:35,130 --> 00:04:37,140
I've also had a pretty fun life

116
00:04:37,140 --> 00:04:40,500
from flying full-size
airplanes and racing cars

117
00:04:40,500 --> 00:04:43,380
to competing for my country
and traveling the world.

118
00:04:43,380 --> 00:04:46,320
If I'd invested all of that
money into the stock market,.

119
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:48,360
then I'd have missed out on so much.

120
00:04:48,360 --> 00:04:50,970
So my answer would be
to invest whatever you

121
00:04:50,970 --> 00:04:53,970
feel comfortable with, but if
you want a more solid answer

122
00:04:53,970 --> 00:04:57,180
then a 70/20/10 rule
is a pretty good guide.

123
00:04:57,180 --> 00:04:59,010
It states that you should split your money

124
00:04:59,010 --> 00:05:03,090
by these percentages,
70% on living expenses,

125
00:05:03,090 --> 00:05:06,600
20% on investments, and
10% on the fun stuff.

126
00:05:06,600 --> 00:05:08,460
Research shows that people who invest

127
00:05:08,460 --> 00:05:11,220
at this level are much better
equipped to ride the ups

128
00:05:11,220 --> 00:05:14,400
and downs of life and also
get ahead of everyone else.

129
00:05:14,400 --> 00:05:17,700
That's all well and good,
but how do I buy a stock?

130
00:05:17,700 --> 00:05:19,470
There are various different apps out there

131
00:05:19,470 --> 00:05:21,360
that allow you to invest in stocks.

132
00:05:21,360 --> 00:05:23,130
I'll leave some links below.

133
00:05:23,130 --> 00:05:26,160
The key is to open the
correct type of account.

134
00:05:26,160 --> 00:05:28,260
You'll often hear people
throwing around the terms,

135
00:05:28,260 --> 00:05:31,830
ROTH IRA, in the USA and
stocks and shares ISA

136
00:05:31,830 --> 00:05:36,720
in the UK, TFSA in Canada
and supers in Australia.

137
00:05:36,720 --> 00:05:38,430
If you don't have one of these accounts

138
00:05:38,430 --> 00:05:39,630
then you're missing out

139
00:05:39,630 --> 00:05:43,020
as they allow you to avoid
paying taxes on your investments,

140
00:05:43,020 --> 00:05:46,320
but they do have limits
because they're so powerful.

141
00:05:46,320 --> 00:05:48,480
A great thing about these
investing apps is they

142
00:05:48,480 --> 00:05:51,810
actually give you the ability
to buy fractional shares.

143
00:05:51,810 --> 00:05:55,890
So rather than buying a
share of Apple for $190,

144
00:05:55,890 --> 00:05:57,990
you can invest as little as $1.

145
00:05:57,990 --> 00:06:00,360
I wish I had this option
when I was younger,

146
00:06:00,360 --> 00:06:01,500
as it would've allowed me

147
00:06:01,500 --> 00:06:03,510
to get some early investing experience

148
00:06:03,510 --> 00:06:05,820
without having to take any big risks.

149
00:06:05,820 --> 00:06:09,540
One of my favorite investing
platforms is Trading 212,

150
00:06:09,540 --> 00:06:11,310
as they do both of these things.

151
