up to a hundred pounds.

177
00:07:11,910 --> 00:07:14,310
Or alternatively, click
the link in a description

178
00:07:14,310 --> 00:07:17,910
to sign up and see exactly
how to access the free share.

179
00:07:17,910 --> 00:07:19,410
Now, the obvious next question

180
00:07:19,410 --> 00:07:21,960
is how do I pick the best stocks?

181
00:07:21,960 --> 00:07:23,490
There are two main ways to attempt

182
00:07:23,490 --> 00:07:25,050
to predict the stock market.

183
00:07:25,050 --> 00:07:28,230
These are called technical
and fundamental analysis.

184
00:07:28,230 --> 00:07:30,930
A good way to think about
this is like a scale.

185
00:07:30,930 --> 00:07:34,050
Usually short-term day
traders are purely focused

186
00:07:34,050 --> 00:07:35,670
on the technical aspects.

187
00:07:35,670 --> 00:07:38,070
This includes looking
at charts and patterns.

188
00:07:38,070 --> 00:07:40,440
They believe they can predict
how the stock will change

189
00:07:40,440 --> 00:07:43,800
in price by judging the highs
and the lows on the graphs.

190
00:07:43,800 --> 00:07:45,330
As a long-term investor,

191
00:07:45,330 --> 00:07:47,940
my strategy is about keeping it simple.

192
00:07:47,940 --> 00:07:51,000
Lots of people talk about
using margin and options,

193
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:53,160
but that's really not
something I worry about.

194
00:07:53,160 --> 00:07:56,610
I'm a lot more focused on the
fundamentals of a company.

195
00:07:56,610 --> 00:07:59,520
This includes the
financials, the leadership,

196
00:07:59,520 --> 00:08:01,410
and the brand recognition,

197
00:08:01,410 --> 00:08:03,750
as I believe this is
where the true information

198
00:08:03,750 --> 00:08:06,900
lies to indicate the
long-term success of a stock.

199
00:08:06,900 --> 00:08:09,300
When I invest in a stock,
I don't have an intention

200
00:08:09,300 --> 00:08:11,760
of selling it for at
least two to five years.

201
00:08:11,760 --> 00:08:14,220
However, like I mentioned, it's a scale,

202
00:08:14,220 --> 00:08:16,140
so I do look at the occasional chart

203
00:08:16,140 --> 00:08:18,330
in order to find the best time to buy.

204
00:08:18,330 --> 00:08:20,160
This approach has helped
me find some really

205
00:08:20,160 --> 00:08:22,342
good investments over the
years rather than just dipping

206
00:08:22,342 --> 00:08:25,080
in and out, trying to
make a profit every day.

207
00:08:25,080 --> 00:08:27,120
But with the majority of my investments

208
00:08:27,120 --> 00:08:29,250
I don't actually do any of this.

209
00:08:29,250 --> 00:08:32,850
That's because I allocate most
of my money to index funds.

210
00:08:32,850 --> 00:08:36,240
This is definitely the best
strategy for most people.

211
00:08:36,240 --> 00:08:38,190
So what's an index fund?

212
00:08:38,190 --> 00:08:41,010
It's a way for the average
person to make more money

213
00:08:41,010 --> 00:08:43,560
than the professionals
with very little effort.

214
00:08:43,560 --> 00:08:44,970
I'm a big football fan

215
00:08:44,970 --> 00:08:46,650
and if you've ever followed any sports,

216
00:08:46,650 --> 00:08:49,350
you'll be familiar with
a lead table like this.

217
00:08:49,350 --> 00:08:50,880
The better your team performs,

218
00:08:50,880 --> 00:08:52,920
the higher up they'll be on the list.

219
00:08:52,920 --> 00:08:55,440
On the other hand, if
they do really badly,

220
00:08:55,440 --> 00:08:57,660
they might be removed
from the league entirely.

221
00:08:57,660 --> 00:09:00,210
This is almost exactly
the same as an index.

222
00:09:00,210 --> 00:09:02,910
All you have to do is switch
out the teams for companies.

223
00:09:02,910 --> 00:09:05,700
Let's take the S&P 500 for example.

224
00:09:05,700 --> 00:09:09,300
This is a list of around 500
of the largest public companies

225
00:09:09,300 --> 00:09:12,450
in the USA, the big dogs
being Amazon, Google,

226
00:09:12,450 --> 00:09:14,445
Apple and Tesla.

227
00:09:14,445 --> 00:09:15,278
Just like the league table,

228
00:09:15,278 --> 00:09:16,500
if a company does poorly,

229
00:09:16,500 --> 00:09:18,330
then they run the risk of being removed

230
00:09:18,330 --> 00:09:19,290
from the list.

231
00:09:19,290 --> 00:09:22,680
With this league table
or index of companies.

232
00:09:22,680 --> 00:09:25,800
You could go and buy stocks
in some of them individually.

233
00:09:25,800 --> 00:09:27,900
However, if something bad happens

234
00:09:27,900 --> 00:09:30,240
to those companies that you've picked,

235
00:09:30,240 --> 00:09:32,040
then you can wave goodbye to your money.

236
00:09:32,040 --> 00:09:36,210
The idea of an index fund
is to be a little bit sneaky

237
00:09:36,210 --> 00:09:37,650
as it allows you to invest

238
00:09:37,650 --> 00:09:41,490
in every single company on
the list with just one click.

239
00:09:41,490 --> 00:09:44,820
Even if a few companies do
terribly, then it's balanced

240
00:09:44,820 --> 00:09:47,100
out by all the companies
doing extremely well.

241
00:09:47,100 --> 00:09:49,680
The average annual return of the S&P 500

242
00:09:49,680 --> 00:09:54,180
over the last 10 years has been 13.6%.

243
00:09:54,180 --> 00:09:57,210
Although this is slightly higher
than the average over time

244
00:09:57,210 --> 00:09:59,790
no one has ever lost any
money if they've bought

245
00:09:59,790 --> 00:10:03,780
and held an S&P 500 index
fund for more than 20 years.

246
00:10:03,780 --> 00:10:04,613
The truth is

247
00:10:04,613 --> 00:10:07,800
that the average actively
managed fund return 2% less

248
00:10:07,800 --> 00:10:09,600
per year than the market in general.

249
00:10:09,600 --> 00:10:12,300
This means that the professionals
on average are doing worse

250
00:10:12,300 --> 00:10:15,840
than index funds, and even if
they end up losing you money,

251
00:10:15,840 --> 00:10:18,450
they still charge you
high fees no matter what.

252
00:10:18,450 --> 00:10:21,540
The reason that index funds
can charge really low fees

253
00:10:21,540 --> 00:10:23,790
is because they're passively managed,

254
00:10:23,790 --> 00:10:25,740
which means they look after themselves

255
00:10:25,740 --> 00:10:28,560
and don't need an expert
to keep adjusting them.

256
00:10:28,560 --> 00:10:33,150
Meaning the fees can be
as low as 0.02% per year.

257
00:10:33,150 --> 00:10:35,130
When I tell people about index funds,

258
00:10:35,130 --> 00:10:37,798
it often blows their minds.

259
00:10:37,798 --> 00:10:39,330
However, when they go
onto an investing app,

260
00:10:39,330 --> 00:10:42,270
they get confused at the
different options and ask

261
00:10:42,270 --> 00:10:44,880
what's the best index fund to invest in?

262
00:10:44,880 --> 00:10:47,460
Well, as I said, I'm
not a financial advisor,

263
00:10:47,460 --> 00:10:48,900
but I have had a lot

264
00:10:48,900 --> 00:10:51,690
of success with three
different types of index funds.

265
00:10:51,690 --> 00:10:54,720
Number one tracks the S&P 500 index.

266
00:10:54,720 --> 00:10:56,940
This is the one we
briefly mentioned before.

267
00:10:56,940 --> 00:10:58,080
The historical return

268
00:10:58,080 --> 00:11:00,523
of eight to 10% has allowed
me to generate a fortune

269
00:11:00,523 --> 00:11:02,160
over the years.

270
00:11:02,160 --> 00:11:04,800
This is due to the power
of compound interest.

271
00:11:04,800 --> 00:11:09,240
The S&P 500 tracks 11
different industries/sectors

272
00:11:09,240 --> 00:11:12,690
and no sector is more
than 30% of the index.

273
00:11:12,690 --> 00:11:14,310
However, it is worth pointing out

274
00:11:14,310 --> 00:11:16,260
that it's a bit tech heavy these days,

275
00:11:16,260 --> 00:11:20,640
with five tech stocks dominating
23% of the entire fund.

276
00:11:20,640 --> 00:11:23,700
It's up to you if you see this
as a positive or a negative.

277
00:11:23,700 --> 00:11:24,870
I personally don't mind

278
00:11:24,870 --> 00:11:27,000
as I believe in the future of technology.

279
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:29,460
There are so many different
index funds that track

280
00:11:29,460 --> 00:11:32,670
the S&P 500, so here are
some of my favorites.

281
00:11:32,670 --> 00:11:34,190
The best I found in the USA

282
00:11:34,190 --> 00:11:37,950
is the V-FIAX Index Fund or the VOO ETF.

283
00:11:37,950 --> 00:11:42,090
The best in the UK would
probably be the VUSA ETF.

284
00:11:42,090 --> 00:11:44,490
The only real difference
between an index fund

285
00:11:44,490 --> 00:11:47,490
and an ETF is that the
ETF can be purchased

286
00:11:47,490 --> 00:11:49,650
or sold at any time throughout the day.

287
00:11:49,650 --> 00:11:50,820
Just like a stock,

288
00:11:50,820 --> 00:11:53,310
index funds can only be purchased in full.

289
00:11:53,310 --> 00:11:54,330
So for example,

290
00:11:54,330 --> 00:11:58,230
if the price is $500, you must pay $500.

291
00:11:58,230 --> 00:11:59,700
An ETF on the other hand,

292
00:11:59,700 --> 00:12:02,070
can be purchased in fractional shares,

293
00:12:02,070 --> 00:12:04,140
which means you don't
have to buy a full share

294
00:12:04,140 --> 00:12:07,560
and instead you can invest
whatever amount you like.

295
00:12:07,560 --> 00:12:09,150
This is great if you just starting

296
00:12:09,150 --> 00:12:11,670
out or want to dollar cost average in.

297
00:12:11,670 --> 00:12:14,400
Personally, I've set up a
direct debit every month

298
00:12:14,400 --> 00:12:15,960
so the money leaves my bank account

299
00:12:15,960 --> 00:12:17,370
without me even noticing.

300
00:12:17,370 --> 00:12:19,500
Really and truly, there
isn't a huge difference

301
00:12:19,500 --> 00:12:21,870
between an index fund and an ETF.

302
00:12:21,870 --> 00:12:24,960
Just consider which one is
best for you, take the plunge.

303
00:12:24,960 --> 00:12:27,810
Number two is a total stock market index.

304
00:12:27,810 --> 00:12:30,420
The total stock market
index has returned investors

305
00:12:30,420 --> 00:12:33,270
an average of 13% each year

306
00:12:33,270 --> 00:12:36,180
over the last 10 years,
which isn't bad at all.

307
00:12:36,180 --> 00:12:39,030
It's the definition of diversification.

308
00:12:39,030 --> 00:12:40,500
You can't really get any more skin

309
00:12:40,500 --> 00:12:42,060
in the game for a lower cost.

310
00:12:42,060 --> 00:12:44,160
If you want to invest
for a long period of time

311
00:12:44,160 --> 00:12:47,460
without having to even check
or even think about it,

312
00:12:47,460 --> 00:12:49,410
then this is most likely the fund for you.

313
00:12:49,410 --> 00:12:52,410
Investing in everything means
you can experience gains

314
00:12:52,410 --> 00:12:54,120
across the entire market,

315
00:12:54,120 --> 00:12:56,490
and unless a crazy crash happens,

316
00:12:56,490 --> 00:12:57,810
you should be okay,

317
00:12:57,810 --> 00:13:00,450
but even if it does crash, with time,

318
00:13:00,450 --> 00:13:01,890
things tend to bounce back.

319
00:13:01,890 --> 00:13:04,800
I've seen three crashes
since I've been an investor,

320
00:13:04,800 --> 00:13:08,730
the.com bubble, the 2008 financial crisis,

321
00:13:08,730 --> 00:13:11,310
and the 2020 COVID crash.

322
00:13:11,310 --> 00:13:13,680
I'm not going to pretend
these crashes didn't hurt,

323
00:13:13,680 --> 00:13:14,670
but long term

324
00:13:14,670 --> 00:13:17,610
every market I've invested
in has bounced back.

325
00:13:17,610 --> 00:13:19,890
The downside to this index is it depends

326
00:13:19,890 --> 00:13:22,650
on the entire market trending upwards.

327
00:13:22,650 --> 00:13:25,050
This means there could
be an individual stock

328
00:13:25,050 --> 00:13:27,570
that you really believe
in that goes to the moon,

329
00:13:27,570 --> 00:13:29,490
but you might not experience those gains

330
00:13:29,490 --> 00:13:31,530
because that stock doesn't play much

331
00:13:31,530 --> 00:13:33,210
of a role within the index fund.

332
00:13:33,210 --> 00:13:36,840
The best I found in the
USA is the VTSAX Index Fund

333
00:13:36,840 --> 00:13:38,697
and the VTI ETF

334
00:13:38,697 --> 00:13:42,780
and the best in the UK is the VWRL ETF.

335
00:13:42,780 --> 00:13:45,870
Number three is the
emerging markets index.

336
00:13:45,870 --> 00:13:48,330
Emerging markets are
predicted by some experts

337
00:13:48,330 --> 00:13:51,480
to be on the rise, and whether
I agree with this or not,

338
00:13:51,480 --> 00:13:53,010
I think it's important for me to have

339
00:13:53,010 --> 00:13:55,770
at least a little bit of
exposure to these markets.

340
00:13:55,770 --> 00:13:58,470
It's all well and good buying the S&P 500,

341
00:13:58,470 --> 00:14:01,290
but when China, or
another emerging country

342
00:14:01,290 --> 00:14:02,730
has some great gains,

343
00:14:02,730 --> 00:14:04,170
you'll end up missing out.

344
00:14:04,170 --> 00:14:06,330
Just as an example of this growth,

345
00:14:06,330 --> 00:14:09,750
when I first traveled to
China around 20 years ago,

346
00:14:09,750 --> 00:14:12,540
I looked into buying an
apartment in Shenzhen.

347
00:14:12,540 --> 00:14:15,900
That real estate was $47,000,

348
00:14:15,900 --> 00:14:18,030
and now it's worth over a million.

349
00:14:18,030 --> 00:14:21,000
This just shows the potential
growth in these markets.

350
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:24,060
Emerging market funds are
definitely the most risky type

351
00:14:24,060 --> 00:14:26,040
of index funds we've discussed.

352
00:14:26,040 --> 00:14:28,050
These funds include stocks from lots

353
00:14:28,050 --> 00:14:30,780
of different growing markets
and could be very heavy

354
00:14:30,780 --> 00:14:32,280
with Chinese companies.

355
00:14:32,280 --> 00:14:34,680
Taking a look at a list
of the largest economies

356
00:14:34,680 --> 00:14:35,513
in the world.

357
00:14:35,513 --> 00:14:38,460
A lot of them are emerging
markets, so it just makes sense

358
00:14:38,460 --> 00:14:41,730
to me to throw a little bit of
money in for diversification.

359
00:14:41,730 --> 00:14:46,470
The best I found in the
U S A is the VEIEX ETF

360
00:14:46,470 --> 00:14:50,940
and in the UK, the VFEM
ETF, but there are also lots

361
00:14:50,940 --> 00:14:52,980
of other emerging market funds available,

362
00:14:52,980 --> 00:14:55,140
so it's worth having a look around.

363
00:14:55,140 --> 00:14:57,330
Now, I know at some
point I need to address

364
00:14:57,330 --> 00:14:59,280
the biggest question around investing,

365
00:14:59,280 --> 00:15:01,980
which is, of course, is investing risky?

366
00:15:01,980 --> 00:15:05,070
It really depends on how you define risk.

367
00:15:05,070 --> 00:15:07,320
You may be scared that you'll lose money.

368
00:15:07,320 --> 00:15:09,510
However, you also face this risk

369
00:15:09,510 --> 00:15:12,960
by not investing, as my
father Mervin found out

370
00:15:12,960 --> 00:15:15,960
if you have a diversified
portfolio of index funds

371
00:15:15,960 --> 00:15:19,290
and keep investing at a gradual
rate each and every year,

372
00:15:19,290 --> 00:15:22,080
then even if there is a stop market crash,

373
00:15:22,080 --> 00:15:24,720
then historical data
shows you should be able

374
00:15:24,720 --> 00:15:25,800
to endure the storm.

375
00:15:25,800 --> 00:15:27,810
A great way to make sure you're protected

376
00:15:27,810 --> 00:15:30,150
in the event of a market crash is to mix

377
00:15:30,150 --> 00:15:33,240
in a few bonds within
your stock portfolio.

378
00:15:33,240 --> 00:15:35,460
These are just a different
type of investment

379
00:15:35,460 --> 00:15:37,680
that are far more stable than stocks

380
00:15:37,680 --> 00:15:40,620
and you can buy these on the
same investment platforms.

381
00:15:40,620 --> 00:15:42,180
In your twenties and thirties,

382
00:15:42,180 --> 00:15:44,220
I wouldn't worry too much about them,

383
00:15:44,220 --> 00:15:46,230
but as you move closer to retirement

384
00:15:46,230 --> 00:15:48,870
it's a good idea to have
more bonds and stocks.

385
00:15:48,870 --> 00:15:51,120
In my opinion, in your younger years,

386
00:15:51,120 --> 00:15:55,080
the biggest risk you can take
is not taking enough risk.

387
00:15:55,080 --> 00:15:57,570
Now, for the question on everyone's mind,

388
00:15:57,570 --> 00:15:59,580
when should I sell my stocks?

389
00:15:59,580 --> 00:16:01,770
It's possibly one of the
most common questions

390
00:16:01,770 --> 00:16:03,570
in the stock investing world.

391
00:16:03,570 --> 00:16:05,070
Knowing when to sell stocks

392
00:16:05,070 --> 00:16:08,280
or hold onto them mostly
depends on your age.

393
00:16:08,280 --> 00:16:10,530
If you're older, you've
likely been investing

394
00:16:10,530 --> 00:16:11,550
for a while and can live

395
00:16:11,550 --> 00:16:14,790
off them during retirement by
gradually selling when needed.

396
00:16:14,790 --> 00:16:17,910
However, if you're younger,
this usually isn't the case.

397
00:16:17,910 --> 00:16:20,640
In fact, if you are in
your twenties to thirties,

398
00:16:20,640 --> 00:16:24,300
there are only three good
reasons to sell your investments.

399
00:16:24,300 --> 00:16:27,360
Number one, you need
money for an emergency.

400
00:16:27,360 --> 00:16:29,430
Hopefully, if you
followed the video so far,

401
00:16:29,430 --> 00:16:30,720
then you won't need to worry

402
00:16:30,720 --> 00:16:32,850
because you've got an
emergency fund to help you

403
00:16:32,850 --> 00:16:34,200
out in times like this.

404
00:16:34,200 --> 00:16:36,570
Number two, you made a bad investment.

405
00:16:36,570 --> 00:16:38,730
If you have individual stocks that appear

406
00:16:38,730 --> 00:16:41,580
to be underperforming consistently,

407
00:16:41,580 --> 00:16:44,940
it may be time to cut your
losses before those losses stack

408
00:16:44,940 --> 00:16:46,020
up even higher.

409
00:16:46,020 --> 00:16:47,370
Before panic selling,

410
00:16:47,370 --> 00:16:49,770
take a good look at the wider industry.

411
00:16:49,770 --> 00:16:52,170
If other goods like it
are also in decline,

412
00:16:52,170 --> 00:16:55,320
then you know it's the
industry, not just your stock.

413
00:16:55,320 --> 00:16:57,150
If everything's doing poorly,

414
00:16:57,150 --> 00:16:59,190
this gives you a bit of extra context.

415
00:16:59,190 --> 00:17:02,370
Number three, you've
achieved a specific goal,

416
00:17:02,370 --> 00:17:04,560
although I don't really recommend it.

417
00:17:04,560 --> 00:17:07,396
If you are investing for short
or medium term goals like,

418
00:17:07,396 --> 00:17:10,440
I don't know, saving up
for a dream vacation,

419
00:17:10,440 --> 00:17:13,800
then it would be a great
idea to set a target price.

420
00:17:13,800 --> 00:17:14,633
This is a figure

421
00:17:14,633 --> 00:17:17,160
at which you would feel
satisfied selling the stock

422
00:17:17,160 --> 00:17:18,780
and enjoying your gains.

423
00:17:18,780 --> 00:17:21,300
The most important thing
to remember is to not

424
00:17:21,300 --> 00:17:22,680
sell your stocks for as long

425
00:17:22,680 --> 00:17:25,890
as possible so they have
the longest time to grow.

426
00:17:25,890 --> 00:17:27,720
Just invest and forget about it,

427
00:17:27,720 --> 00:17:30,870
until you want to stop
investing and take your profits.

428
00:17:30,870 --> 00:17:33,990
This thinking will also help
you avoid panic selling.

429
00:17:33,990 --> 00:17:36,783
If you wanna know exactly how
I pick my individual stocks,

430
00:17:36,783 --> 00:17:38,790
then you can check out this video next,

431
00:17:38,790 --> 00:17:40,590
but don't click on it just yet.

432
00:17:40,590 --> 00:17:42,870
Make sure to subscribe if
you want to grow your wealth.

433
00:17:42,870 --> 00:17:44,703
Okay, I'll see you over there.

